      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, you caught me! I slipped up and called it a \"goblin\" because, honestly, the concept of non-locality is so mischievous and tricky that it feels like a goblin hiding in the equations, pranking our classical intuitions. It's a bit of a slip of the tongue, but I think the goblin analogy stuck because quantum mechanics often feels like a world where the rules are written by a mischievous goblin who loves to confuse us.\n\nTo answer your question directly: there is no \"invisible force\" or signal traveling between them in the way a wave travels through water. If there were, it would violate the cosmic speed limit (the speed of light), which is why Einstein was so bothered by it. Instead, the \"trick\" is that the particles don't have definite properties until they are measured. They exist as a single, unified wave function. When you measure one, you aren't sending a message to the other; you are simply collapsing the shared reality of the whole system. It's more like two goblins who are actually one spirit split in two; if one goblin sneezes, the other sneezes instantly because they are the same entity, not because",
